len]] head\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2020\n|rowspan=2|Deadpool 2\n|[[Deadpool]]\n|Twin katanas and pistols\n|rowspan=2|[[Deadpool 2]] version\n|-\n|[[Negasonic Teenage Warhead]]\n|2 energy effect pieces\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2020\n|rowspan=2|Old Man Logan\n|[[Old Man Logan]] and Bruce Banner Jr.\n|Cowboy hat\n|Retool of the Warlock wave Old Man Logan with a new head and trench coat\n|-\n|[[Alternative versions of Hawkeye#Old Man Logan|Old Man Hawkeye]]\n|Bow, arrow and bag\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Deluxe/vehicles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!width=5%|'''Release'''\n!width=7%|'''Figure'''\n!width=20%|'''Accessories'''\n!width=68%|'''Description'''\n|-\n|rowspan=8|2020\n|[[Ultimate Captain America]]\n|Motorcycle, shield, combat knife, machine gun, pistol, holster and removable helmet\n|World War 2 version\n|-\n|[[Cosmic Ghost Rider]]\n|Hell Cycle, two blasters, flaming chain and hover effect piece\n|\n|-\n|[[Punisher]]\n|Motorcycle, shotgun, baseball bat, alternate head and viking helmet\n|[[Punisher War Journal]] version\n|-\n|[[Venom (Marvel Comics character)|Venom]]\n|\n|Repaint of the Monster Venom BAF in classic colors\n|-\n|[[War Machine]]\n|2 shoulder cannons, 5 blast effect pieces and alternate unmasked head\n|Classic version\n|-\n|[[Apocalypse (comics)|Apocalypse]]\n|Skull and alternate head\n|[[Age of Apocalypse]] version\n|-\n|[[Nimrod (comics)|Nimrod]]\n|Alternate classic head\n|[[Powers of X]] version\n|}\n\n===Amazon===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!width=5%|'''Release'''\n!width=7%|'''Figure'''\n!width=20%|'''Accessories'''\n!width=68%|'''Description'''\n|-\n|2020\n|[[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]]\n|Alternate head and bone claw hands\n|[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]] version\n|}\n\n===Target===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!width=5%|'''Release'''\n!width=7%|'''Figure'''\n!width=20%|'''Accessories'''\n!width=68%|'''Description'''\n|-\n|rowspan=4|2020\n|[[Stan Lee]]\n|Autographed Captain America shield and chess board\n|[[The Avengers (2012 film)]] version<br>Originally scheduled to be released in 2018 as a Build-A-Figure whose parts would've been packaged with the Target-exclusive Erik Killmonger/Everett Ross and Falcon/Winter Soldier two-packs, but was delayed for unknown reasons.\n|-\n|[[Red Hulk]]\n|Alternate hands\n|\n|-\n|[[Iron Man]]\n|Alternate hands and 4 blast effect pieces\n|[[Avengers (2020 video game)]] Starboost armor version\n|-\n|[[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Storm]]\n|2 lightning effect pieces and alternate head\n|Classic [[Giant-Size X-Men]] version\n|}\n\n===Walmart===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!width=5%|'''Release'''\n!width=7%|'''Figure'''\n!width=20%|'''Accessories'''\n!width=68%|'''Description'''\n|-\n|2020\n|[[Captain America]]\n|Symbiote shield\n|[[Venomverse|Venomized]] version\n|-\n|2020\n|[[Cable (comics)|Cable]]\n|Energy rifle and teddy bear\n|[[Deadpool 2]] version\n|}\n\n==See also==\n[[Toy Biz]] had several related lines of toys of [[Marvel Comics]] characters, often exhibiting comparable articulation, and similar scale.\n* [[DC Multiverse (toy line)|DC Multiverse]]\n* [[DC Universe Classics]]\n* Fantastic Four Classics\n* [[Hulk Classics]]\n* [[Iron Man: The Armored Avenger]]\n* [[Spider-Man Classics]]\n* [[Spider-Man Classics|Spider-Man]]\n* [[X-Men Classics]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050403174956/http://www.toybiz.com/showbrand.htm?id=2 ToyBiz.com] Official ToyBiz site\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070328173159/http://www.hasbro.com/marvel/default.cfm?page=Products%2FMarvelLegends Hasbro.com] Official Hasbro site\n* [http://marvelousnews.com/ MarvelousNews.com] Daily Marvel Legends News, Complete Photo Database and Collector Community\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071030043812/http://www.stashmatic.com/entities/list?Series=Marvel+Legends&entity_id=92 Stashmatic.com] Marvel Legends database with images\n* [http://marvellegends.net/ MarvelLegends.Net] Marvel Legends Photo Database, News and Forums\n* [http://marvellegends.info/ marvellegends.info] The Complete Guide to Marvel Legends\n* [http://marvellegends.hyves.nl/ marvellegends.hyves.nl] A Marvel Legends site from the Netherlands\n* [https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/toy-collector-action-figure/id541765272?mt=8 Free Marvel Legends iOS Checklist Application]\n* [https://www.actionfigure411.com/marvel/ Visual and Price guides for Marvel Legends Action Figures]\n{{Superhero toy lines}}\n{{Hasbro}}\n\n[[Category:Hasbro products]]\n[[Category:2000s toys]]\n[[Category:2010s toys]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics action figure lines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Action figure line}}\n{{about|the action figure line of Marvel characters|the video game formerly titled \"Marvel Legends\"|Marvel: Ultimate Alliance|the comic book|Marvel Legends (comics)}}\n{{redirect|Marvel Icon|the imprint|Icon Comics}}\n\n{| class=\"infobox bordered\" style=\"width: 25em; text-align: left; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ style=\"font-size: larger;\" | '''Marvel Legends'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Marvel legends logo.png]]\n4\", 6\", 8\", and 12\" Action Figure Toy Line\n|-\n! [[Toy Biz]]:\n| 2002\u20132006\n|-\n! [[Hasbro]]:\n| 2006\u2013Present\n|}\n'''Marvel Legends''' is an [[action figure]] line based on the characters of [[Marvel Comics]], initially produced by [[Toy Biz]], then by [[Hasbro]]. This line is in the {{convert|6|in|mm|adj=on}} scale, with spin-off lines in the {{convert|4|in|mm|adj=on}}, {{convert|8|in|mm|adj=on}}, and {{convert|12|in|mm|adj=on}} scale.\n\nThe line initially began as a spin-off of the [[Spider-Man Classics]] line, which were also produced by Toy Biz. At its inception in 2002, the Marvel Legends line copied the clam-shell packaging and the included comic book that had shipped with the Spider-Man Classics line. Beginning January 1, 2007, Hasbro became the new license holder to the rights to produce toys and games based upon the Marvel Universe. The new Hasbro packaging did not include a comic book and the new molds eliminated finger joints, which were a mainstay during the Toy Biz era, but the company did continue with the theme of Build-A-Figure pieces. During the late 2000s, production on the Marvel Legends line slowed down to the point where it was rumored that it may be cancelled, but Hasbro revealed (at the 2010 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]) that due to fan requests and the upcoming movies based on Marvel characters, the line would be making a comeback in 2012, and in January 2012, Marvel Legends returned to store shelves.\n\nAt the 2013 San Diego Comic Con, Hasbro announced that Marvel Legends would be given a new start as the ''Marvel Legends Infinite Series'' starting with the [[Mandroid]] series. Initially, the Marvel Legends line has used the \"chase\" concept to introduce figures based on less popular or recognisable characters. These got their nickname by being shipped in fewer quantities than the rest of the figures, thus causing collectors to ''chase'' after them. Eventually, rather than entirely new figures, the chase concept evolved into variants (such as an alternate head or a different colour scheme) of a figure released in that same series. These figures retained being sought-after by collectors. A Marvel Legends [[Flatman (comics)|Flatman]] \"figure\" was included as a joke cut-out in the GLX-Mas Special (2005). It featured \"infinite\" points of articulation and three action phrases (to be said with one's own voice).\n\n==Toy Biz==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=5%|'''Series'''\n!width=5%|'''Release'''\n!width=15%|'''Figure'''\n!width=25%|'''Accessories'''\n!width=25%|'''Description'''\n!width=25%|'''Comic'''\n|-\n|rowspan=7|1\n|rowspan=7|May 2002\n|[[Captain America]]\n|destroyed building and American flag display\n|\n|Captain America (1968) #109\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Hulk]]\n|rowspan=2|destroyed wall stand\n|bendable fingers\n|rowspan=2|Incredible Hulk (1968) #314\n|-\n